See https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/issues/2577

It is currently illegal to write:

```csharp
interface I
{
    int a() => 1;
}    
struct S : I
{
    int b() => a() + 5; // CS0103: The name 'a' does not exist in the current context
}
```

This is apparently in order to prevent implicit boxing of the `this`.

However it seems to me that the JIT should always be able to devirtualize the call here, in the same way as it devirtualizes `Equals`, `ToString`, `GetHashCode` and `GetType`.

If so it would be useful if the JIT could guarantee this, and then C# would be able to take advantage of such a guarantee to improve the experience using DIMs with structs.

