The following test fails against a preview6 nightly:

```C#
[Fact]
public void Emoji()
{
    // Arrange & Act
    using (var stringWriter = new StringWriter())
    {
        HtmlEncoder.Default.Encode(stringWriter, "😂2");
        var encoded = stringWriter.ToString();
        Assert.Equal("&#x1F602;2", encoded);
    }
}
```
The "2" directly after the emoji gets truncated. If you add a second '2' after the first, it succeeds. Also of note is that the `Encode(string value)` overload does NOT seem to suffer from this problem.

I would assume that this would be true of other emojis and/or high unicode characters.

